P4: Simple Chat Server

Authors
Neil Barot (nnb35)
Hriday Adani (hva6)

Build
make

Run
./chatd <port>

What We Built
We implemented a simple chat server in C that accepts client connections, handles screen names, forwards public and private messages, supports status updates, and answers WHO queries.
We used a select-based event loop so one server process can manage multiple connected clients at once.

Test Plan
We tested the server with a mix of protocol-level and behavior-level checks.

1. Name handling
   valid names, duplicate names, illegal characters, and names that are too long
2. Status updates
   empty status, normal status, illegal characters, and status strings that are too long
3. Public and private messaging
   broadcast to #all, private delivery to one user, and unknown recipients
4. WHO queries
   single-user lookups, room-wide lookups, and unknown users
5. Protocol errors
   malformed headers, unknown message types, bad lengths, and missing separators
6. Connection behavior
   login first, multiple clients at once, and disconnecting clients

Notes on testing
We used the supplied client and raw binaries from clients.tar for lab-style testing. On the lab machines, client can be used for normal chat flows and raw can be used to send exact protocol frames and check error handling.

Implementation Notes
We kept the submission focused on the required pieces: the server source, the Makefile, the AUTHOR file, and this README.

